50|$|According to {{the latest}} issue of the Index, for 2012 Norway and Sweden kept their top {{positions}} from 2010 with scores of 90.4 and 88.3, respectively. Chad and Sudan remained {{at the bottom of the}} index with scores of 23.3 and 19.2, respectively. Countries that had the most changes from the 2010 index included Kenya, which went from 90th place to 86th place. The Index suggests that this change occurred because the Kenyan government enacted new policies mandating equal pay for equal work, and made sexual harassment in the workplace illegal. Thailand moved up one place from 2010 to 2012; the index claimed that Thai women gained greater support for business skills training more than any of their regional counterparts. Saudi Arabia’s score increased from 35.9 in 2010 to 39.7 in 2012 mainly due to a ministerial order that included <b>equal</b> <b>remuneration</b> for men and women.|$|E
